        <!-- Overview -->
        <h2>📌 What is SLSA?</h2>
        <p>SLSA (pronounced “salsa”) provides a set of incrementally adoptable security guidelines that help both producers and consumers verify that software artifacts haven’t been tampered with and can be traced back to their source. The core of SLSA is <strong>provenance</strong> – verifiable metadata describing how an artifact was built.</p>

        <!-- Levels grid -->
        <h2>📈 SLSA Build Levels (v1.0)</h2>
        <div class="card-grid">
            <div class="level-card">
                <h3><span class="level-number">0</span> No guarantees</h3>
                <p>No provenance produced. No security expectations.</p>
                <span class="tag">default</span>
            </div>
            <div class="level-card">
                <h3><span class="level-number">1</span> Provenance exists</h3>
                <p>Provenance is generated, but it can be forged by the build process.</p>
                <span class="tag">scripted build</span>
            </div>
            <div class="level-card">
                <h3><span class="level-number">2</span> Hosted / signed</h3>
                <p>Provenance is generated by a hosted build platform and signed. Prevents tampering after build.</p>
                <span class="tag">signed provenance</span>
            </div>
            <div class="level-card">
                <h3><span class="level-number">3</span> Hardened builds</h3>
                <p>Provenance cannot be forged even by the build process: isolated, ephemeral environments, and secrets protected.</p>
                <span class="tag">non‑forgeable</span>
            </div>
        </div>

        <!-- Level 3 deep dive -->
        <h2>🛡️ SLSA Level 3 — Hardened Builds</h2>
